1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,450
Last time, we used a violin plot to look at

2

00:00:02,450  -->  00:00:05,875
the relationship between vehicle class and fuel efficiency.

3

00:00:05,875  -->  00:00:09,449
Now, we'll use box plots to summarize that relationship.

4

00:00:09,449  -->  00:00:14,105
Just substitute violin plot for box plot, and we've got our output.

5

00:00:14,105  -->  00:00:15,820
The bottom of each box,

6

00:00:15,820  -->  00:00:19,990
indicates the first quartile and the top of each box, the third quartile.

7

00:00:19,989  -->  00:00:23,034
The central line is the median of each group.

8

00:00:23,035  -->  00:00:26,079
Whiskers branch out toward the min and max and each group,

9

00:00:26,079  -->  00:00:30,164
with outliers depicted as individual points past a maximum whisker length.

10

00:00:30,164  -->  00:00:32,280
That depends on each group's box height.

11

00:00:32,280  -->  00:00:35,509
The taller each box, the wider the whiskers can be.

12

00:00:35,509  -->  00:00:39,034
The box plot supports the observations that we made in the last video,

13

00:00:39,034  -->  00:00:43,959
regarding the relative order and variability in fuel efficiencies by vehicle class.

14

00:00:43,960  -->  00:00:45,969
If we move back to the violin plot,

15

00:00:45,969  -->  00:00:49,259
now you can understand what was plotted in each violin area.

16

00:00:49,259  -->  00:00:52,774
The thicker black region represents the interquartile range,

17

00:00:52,774  -->  00:00:55,989
with the white dot in each violin, the medians.

18

00:00:55,990  -->  00:00:59,420
I actually prefer the inner equals quartile parameters setting.

19

00:00:59,420  -->  00:01:02,795
Which only plots the quartiles as dashed lines.

20

00:01:02,795  -->  00:01:06,174
The line with the larger dashes are the medians,

21

00:01:06,174  -->  00:01:10,129
and the lines with the shorter dashes on either side, the quartiles.
